TY  - JOUR
T1  - Relation of Dominant Problems to Stages of Growth in Technology-Based New Ventures
AU  - Kazanjian, Robert K.
Y1  - 1988/06/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256548
DO  - 10.5465/256548
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 257
EP  - 279
VL  - 31
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Two studies investigating the growth patterns of new ventures are presented. In the first study, a stage-of-growth model theorized to apply specifically to technology-based new ventures was developed from two cases. Stages are described as a configuration of organizational design variables representing a firm's response to the sets of dominant problems it faces at sequential times. The second study explored relationships between stages of growth and a theorized pattern of dominant problems using a data base of 105 firms. Partial support emerged for the link between dominant problems and stages of growth.
AB  - Two studies investigating the growth patterns of new ventures are presented. In the first study, a stage-of-growth model theorized to apply specifically to technology-based new ventures was developed from two cases. Stages are described as a configuration of organizational design variables representing a firm's response to the sets of dominant problems it faces at sequential times. The second study explored relationships between stages of growth and a theorized pattern of dominant problems using a data base of 105 firms. Partial support emerged for the link between dominant problems and stages of growth.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256548
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256548
